What are Lubricants in Power Generation and Why is Demand Increasing?
Lubricants used in power generation are specialized industrial fluids formulated to minimize friction, reduce wear, dissipate heat, and protect critical equipment operating under demanding conditions. These lubricants are widely used in gas turbines, steam turbines, hydroelectric turbines, compressors, generators, transformers, and auxiliary equipment to ensure smooth operation, reduce energy losses, and maximize equipment reliability.

Modern power plants increasingly require lubricants capable of operating under higher temperatures, heavier loads, and longer maintenance intervals. Continuous innovations in synthetic base oils, advanced additive technologies, oxidation resistance, corrosion protection, and environmentally acceptable lubricant (EAL) formulations are enabling utilities and industrial operators to improve plant efficiency while meeting increasingly stringent environmental and operational standards.

